definition.value: A wide range of behaviors of an offensive nature. It is commonly understood as behavior that demeans, humiliates or embarrasses a person, and it is characteristically identified by its unlikelihood in terms of social and moral reasonableness. In the legal sense, these are behaviors that appear to be disturbing, upsetting or threatening.
A form of harassment using electronic means.

Quarreling or upsetting people on the Internet to distract and sow discord by posting inflammatory and digressive, extraneous, or off-topic messages in an online community (such as a newsgroup, forum, chat room, or blog) with the intent of provoking readers into displaying emotional responses and normalizing tangential discussion, whether for the troll's amusement or a specific gain.
Participating in debate posing as an actual or potential ally who has concerns that need to be addressed before becoming an ally.
Methods of contraception in which physical, chemical, or biological means are used to prevent the sperm from reaching the fertilizable ovum.
Contraception which utilizes any of various chemicals.
Contraceptive methods that act on the endocrine system, usually using steroid hormones.
Contraceptive techniques applied after sexual intercourse.
Contraception provided surgically or as the result of a surgical process.
Hormonal contraception taken orally.
Hormonal contraception applied through the skin.
Hormonal contraception injected into the skin.
Any of various contraceptive techniques placed within the uterus.
Intrauterine contraception techniques utilizing non-hormonal mechanisms.
Intrauterine contraception techniques utilizing hormonal mechanisms.
Contraceptive techniques applied before sexual intercourse.
Contraceptive techniques applied during sexual intercourse.
Contraception taken following the postpartum period.
Contraceptive methods designed for men.
Contraceptive methods designed for women.
Contraceptive methods related to the penis.
Contraceptive methods related to the vagina.
Contraception provided in a medical manner, either hormonally or surgically.
Surgical operations on the nose and nasal cavity.
Contraception using non-medical methods.
Contraception utilizing a sheath.
Contraceptive methods which use chemicals to kill spermatozoa.
Penile contraception utilizing non-medical methods.
Barrier contraception which is placed in the vagina.
Barrier contraception which is placed in the penis.
Use of an animal's immune system to prevent it from fertilizing offspring. Contraceptives of this type are not currently available for human use.
Contraceptive methods which are long-lasting, but not permanent, usually lasting years.
Contraceptive methods which can be undone.
Contraceptive methods which cannot be undone, or which cause permanent infertility.
A small, often T-shaped contraceptive device that is inserted into a person's uterus to prevent pregnancy.
A type of intrauterine device which contains copper.
An intrauterine device that releases the hormone levonorgestrel into the uterus.
A plastic surgical operation on the nose, either reconstructive, restorative, or cosmetic.
A form of contraceptive which is injected into the body, usually either in the muscle or under the skin.
A form of hormonal contraception and progestogen-only contraception that are administered by injection and providing long-lasting birth control.
A form of hormonal birth control. They consist of monthly injections of combined formulations containing an estrogen and a progestin to prevent pregnancy.
A sheath-shaped barrier device, used during sexual intercourse to reduce the probability of pregnancy or a sexually transmitted infection (STI).
A condom that is rolled onto an erect penis before intercourse and works by forming a physical barrier which blocks semen from entering the body of a sexual partner.
A condom that is worn internally within the vagina to prevent exposure to ejaculated semen or other body fluids.
A device used for the purposes of barrier contraception.
Construction of the urethra following damage to it or its destruction.
Contraception revolving behaviors of at least one partner during, before, and/or after coitus.
Contraception revolving behaviors of at least one partner during coitus.
Contraception revolving behaviors of at least one partner before and/or after coitus.

A type of birth control that is designed to be taken orally. It includes a combination of an estrogen (usually ethinylestradiol) and a progestogen (specifically a progestin). When taken correctly, it alters the menstrual cycle to eliminate ovulation and prevent pregnancy.
